# part 10: MariaDB
1- install mariadb from the local repo that was created earlier.
2- open ports in iptables from mariadb.
3- create database , user(note: handle permissions).
4- connect to the database created in step 3 using the new user (with password)
Example schema :
Create a MariaDB database called studentdb on rhce1 and add ten records each containing “student
firstname” (Allen, David, Mary, Dennis, Joseph, Dennis, Ritchie, Robert, David, and Mary), “student
lastname” (Brown,Brown, Green, Green, Black, Black, Salt, Salt, Suzuki, and Chen), program enrolled in (3 x
mechanical, 3 x electrical,and 4 x computer science), expected graduation year (2 x 2017, 3 x 2018, 5 x
2020), and a student number (110-001 to 110-010)

dnf install mariadb-server -y       		# Install MariaDB server package
systemctl enable --now mariadb     	        # Enable and start MariaDB service
firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=mysql    # Allow MySQL/MariaDB service through firewall
firewall-cmd --reload                           # Apply firewall changes
mysql -u root -p				# Login as root to MariaDB
# Inside MariaDB prompt:
CREATE DATABASE studentdb;                             		# Create database studentdb
DROP USER IF EXISTS 'studentuser'@'%';                  	# Remove existing user if exists
CREATE USER 'studentuser'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'password'; 	# Create new user accessible from any host
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON studentdb.* TO 'studentuser'@'%'; 	# Grant full privileges on studentdb
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;                                    	        # Reload privileges to apply changes
# Create the students table
USE studentdb;                                  
CREATE TABLE students (
    student_number VARCHAR(10) PRIMARY KEY,
    first_name VARCHAR(50),
    last_name VARCHAR(50),
    program_enrolled VARCHAR(50),
    graduation_year INT
);                                                   
# Insert records into students table
INSERT INTO students (student_number, first_name, last_name, program_enrolled, graduation_year) VALUES
('110-001', 'Allen', 'Brown', 'Mechanical', 2017),
('110-002', 'David', 'Brown', 'Mechanical', 2017),
('110-003', 'Mary', 'Green', 'Mechanical', 2018),
('110-004', 'Dennis', 'Green', 'Electrical', 2018),
('110-005', 'Joseph', 'Black', 'Electrical', 2018),
('110-006', 'Dennis', 'Black', 'Electrical', 2020),
('110-007', 'Ritchie', 'Salt', 'Computer Science', 2020),
('110-008', 'Robert', 'Salt', 'Computer Science', 2020),
('110-009', 'David', 'Suzuki', 'Computer Science', 2020),
('110-010', 'Mary', 'Chen', 'Computer Science', 2020);  	# Add 10 sample student records
SELECT * FROM students;                             		# Verify the inserted records
EXIT;                                           	        # Exit MariaDB prompt

mysql -u studentuser -p -h 127.0.0.1 studentdb      		# Connect to studentdb as studentuser

notes:
Allow inbound connections to port 3306/tcp in the firewall on the server where MariaDB is running.
This can be done using either firewall or iptables.
To allow remote or local clients to connect to MariaDB/MySQL database.
To ensure the user can perform only allowed operations on the database.
% allows the user to connect from any host.
connect to the database created in step 3 using the new user (with password): Connecting with the new user verifies that the account works, has the correct permissions, and can access and modify the database as intended.
GRANT is used to allow the new user to actually use the database. Without it, the user exists but can’t read, write, or modify any data.
